dotProject: 	German Localisation - Deutsche Lokalisierung

Policy and Standardisation
--------------------------
--------------------------

0) Aim
------
This translation shall be standardised upon the following guidelines.

In short:
---------
The translation shall:
a) correspond to usual project management terminology
b) correspond to usual free libre open source software terminology 
c) be as general as possible
d) as near to the original as possible
e) be spelled along the rules of 'Der Duden'
f) fit the context
g) shall not be over-zealous
h) correct meaning of wrong original terminology
i) be neutral w.r.t. target groups
j) be neutral w.r.t. industries/areas of use



Terms and expressions
-------------------------
The best German equivalent for a given english term/expression should be found by
a) clarifying how the term/expression is usually translated in project management context
b) determining the usual term/expression in major FLOSS applications/frameworks such as:
	 OpenOffice.org, GNOME, Firefox, Thunderbird, etc.
c) respecting the general validity of the expression
d) respecting the proximity to the original

Spelling
-------------
e) The spelling is bound to the German standard "Der Duden", http://de.wiktionary.org or http://www.dict.cc
	 respectively. In case of doubt 'Der Duden' rules.

Context
-----------
f) The best translation is not necessarily the direct one. It shall be determined by evaluation of the context.
g) Translation shall not be forced (i.e. in general Project Management -> Projektmanagement and not Projektverwaltung).

Deviations:
--------------
The translation may deviate from the original in case
h) of the original being proven to be wrong

Neutrality
---------------
i) This localisation distribution shall be neutral in the sense of Target Group Neutrality.
	 The main problem is that the english 'you' has two German interpretations:
		i) the formal 'Sie/Sie'
		ii)the informal 'Du/Ihr'
	 
	 Consequently, the english 'you' must be translated to the german equivalent of 'one', 'man'.

		"Please fill in your last name!" => "Bitte den Nachnamen eingeben!"
		"Click on 'Submit' and ..." => "Man klicke auf 'Abschicken' und ..."

j)  This localisation shall be neutral in the sense of industry neutrality, 
		so the translations should refer to general project management terminology 
		and not to specific terminology in one particular area.


